00:34:14.930 --> 00:34:19.550
We navigate through the diverse
landscape of invisible illness

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:22.000
and common challenges.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:26.110
For instance, the difficulty,
fatigue, and energy management,

00:34:26.110 --> 00:34:31.100
as I recently told,
I need to take some breaks

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:32.800
from chronic fatigue syndrome.

00:34:35.490 --> 00:34:41.060
When I'm attending an
event like a virtual event,

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:45.090
it's really interesting
that we can accommodate this

00:34:45.090 --> 00:34:48.717
by offering flexible
participation options,

00:34:48.718 --> 00:34:51.190
like the WP Accessibility Day

00:34:51.190 --> 00:34:56.730
for instance, where the
sessions are getting recorded,

00:34:56.730 --> 00:35:07.867
and how long it takes to process
all those videos from 24 hours,

00:35:07.867 --> 00:35:12.620
they are offered as videos
you can re-watch, and watch

00:35:12.620 --> 00:35:16.150
in your own pace,
and pause in between.

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:21.130
And there are also
breaks scheduled.

00:35:21.130 --> 00:35:25.390
The same goes for in person events.

00:35:25.390 --> 00:35:32.450
You can offer quiet and comfortable
spaces for attendees to rest,

00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:38.110
and make sure that you can
have some seating positions,

00:35:38.110 --> 00:35:42.134
like a chair or a
bench in the hallways,

00:35:42.135 --> 00:35:44.980
that people like me who need

00:35:44.980 --> 00:35:52.510
to take some breaks for long walking
distances can take the break,

00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:57.080
and don't look for any
ways to sit on a floor.

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:02.420
Because when I sit on a
floor, I can't get back up.

00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:08.120
And also have a flexible schedule
so that you have a mix of short

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:10.390
and longer sessions with breaks.

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:14.640
The same goes for the
cognitive overload.

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:23.960
Like for virtual meetups, settings
are important to provide a clear

00:36:23.960 --> 00:36:26.920
and concise agenda ahead of time.

00:36:26.920 --> 00:36:33.250
And also give visual aids,
and some infographics

00:36:33.250 --> 00:36:37.690
to simplify the complex
topics, for instance.

00:36:37.690 --> 00:36:43.770
And keep the content of
slides as short as possible,

00:36:43.770 --> 00:36:50.770
and use a good hierarchy
so that someone can grasp

00:36:50.770 --> 00:36:53.800
the content much easier.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:58.290
For the in-person event,
accommodation is the same.

00:36:58.290 --> 00:37:02.420
Like the quiet areas,
there’s also quiet rooms

00:37:02.420 --> 00:37:08.380
where attendees can take a
break from sensory overloads,

00:37:08.380 --> 00:37:15.890
and also provide different form of
materials or summaries for sessions.

00:37:15.890 --> 00:37:23.890
It is quite an organizational burden
sometimes to accommodate such thing,

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:29.000
but in the end,
everyone benefits from this.

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:35.280
The same goes with social anxiety.

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:42.160
The pandemic was also
playing a big part,

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:50.160
and some people have learned
that they don't do well in groups

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:56.580
of people, and they may
not all have a disorder,

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:59.510
but sometimes a spectrum of this.

00:37:59.510 --> 00:38:10.033
And we can, as organizers, ensure
that we allow participation via chat

00:38:10.033 --> 00:38:11.710
instead of a video.

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:16.270
Or that we allow
anonymous participation,

00:38:16.270 --> 00:38:21.080
where they can use pseudonyms
or remain anonymous.

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:27.940
Also, with in-person events,
we can create introvert zones

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:30.550
with less sensory overload.

00:38:30.550 --> 00:38:35.504
